definition.value: Members of the class of benzyl alcohols substituted by at least one methyl group.
Any member of the class of  butanals carrying a methyl substituent at an unspecified position.
Any member of the class of  butanoyl-CoAs having methylbutanoyl as the acyl substituent.
Any member of the class of catechols carrying one or more methyl substituents.
Any member of the class of cytidines that is cytidine substituted by at least one methyl group.
A 2-aminopurine that is guanine bearing a single methyl substituent.
Any guanosine carrying one or more methyl substituents.
A tricarboxylic acid that is isocitric acid substituted by a methyl group alpha- to one of the carboxylic acid groups.
A dicarboxylic acid that is succinic acid carrying hydroxy and methyl substituents at positions 2 and 3 respectively.
An  alkylmercury compound in which the  alkyl group specified is methyl.
Any naphthalene carrying one or more methyl substituents.

An aromatic amide that is N-(2,6-diethylphenyl)acetamide substituted by a methoxymethyl group at at the nitrogen atom while one of the hydrogens of the methyl group has been replaced by a chlorine atom.
A pyrido[4,3-b]indole compound having a 5-methyl-1H-imidazol-4-ylmethyl group at the 2-position.
A propanoyl-CoA substituted by a methyl group on the propanoyl side chain.
A member of the class of  pseudouridines that is pseudouridine substituted by a methyl group at unspecified position.

A member of the class of isoquinolinonaphthyridines that is 5,6-dihydroisoquinolino[2,1-b][2,7]naphthyridin-8-one bearing additional hydroxy, methoxy and 1-hydroxyethyl substituents at positions 2, 3 and 12.
Any member of the class of pyridines that carries at least one methyl substituent.
A group of heterocyclic compounds based on the N-methylated 5,6,7,8-tetrahydropteroic acid skeleton conjugated with one or more L-glutamic acid or L-glutamate units.
A uridine bearing one or more methyl substituents.
An isoquinoline alkaloid that is 1',2'-didehydroemetan bearing two hydroxy substituents at positions 6' and 9 as well as three methoxy substituents at positions 7', 10 and 11.
A racemate composed of equimolar amounts of (R)- and (S)-mevalonate.
A racemate composed of equimolar amounts of (R)- and (S)-mevalonic acid.
Mineralocorticoids are a class of steroid hormones that regulate water and electrolyte metabolism.
A family of aziridine-containing natural products isolated from Streptomyces caespitosus or Streptomyces lavendulae.
A member of the class of beta-carbolines that is tubulosan bearing methoxy groups at positions 10 and 11 as well as a hydroxy group at position 9.
A molecule all atoms of which have the same atomic number.

In mass spectrometry, a molecular ion is an ion formed by the removal from (positive ions) or addition to (negative ions) a molecule of one or more electrons without fragmentation of the molecular structure.
Any polyatomic entity that is an electrically neutral entity consisting of more than one atom.

A member of the class of isoquinolinonaphthyridines that is 5,6-dihydroisoquinolino[2,1-b][2,7]naphthyridin-8-one bearing additional hydroxy, methoxy and vinyl substituents at positions 2, 3 and 12 respectively.
A molybdopterin to which a metal or metal oxide is coordinated, and that acts as a prosthetic group.

A group of neurotransmitters and neuromodulators that contain one amino group that is connected to an aromatic ring by ethylene group  (-CH2-CH2-). Monoamines are derived from the aromatic amino acids phenylalanine, tyrosine, histidine and tryptophan.
An organic heterotetracyclic compound that is an alkaloidal glycoside isolated from Alangium salviifolium.
